async ban_members(guild_id: int, user_ids: list[int]) → None | AsyncIterable[ClientResponse][source]

The ban_members function is a coroutine that takes in a guild_id and user_ids list. It then iterates through the users list, popping off the first user id from the user_ids list and passing it to ban_member function of each client. The response from each client is yielded back to whatever called this function.

Parameters:

  • self – Represent the instance of the class

  • guild_id – int: Specify the guild to ban the user from

  • user_ids – list[int]: Store the list of user ids that will be banned

Returns:

A union of none or an asynciterable[clientresponse]

async get_channels(guild_id: int) → None | AsyncIterable[ClientResponse][source]

The get_channels function is a coroutine that takes in a guild_id and returns an AsyncIterable of ClientResponse objects. The function iterates through the users list, calling get_channels on each user object with the given guild_id as its argument. It then yields each response to be used by other functions.

Parameters:

  • self – Refer to the current instance of a class

  • guild_id – int: Specify the guild id of the channels you want to get

Returns:

An asynciterable of clientresponse objects or None

async get_roles(guild_id: int) → None | AsyncIterable[ClientResponse][source]

The get_roles function is a coroutine that takes in a guild_id and returns an AsyncIterable of ClientResponse objects. The function iterates through the users attribute, which is an array of User objects, and calls the get_roles function on each user object. The get_roles function returns a ClientResponse object for each user.

Parameters:

  • self – Refer to the current instance of the class

  • guild_id – int: Specify the guild id of the server you want to get roles from

async unban_members(guild_id: int, user_ids: list[int]) → None | AsyncIterable[ClientResponse][source]

The unban_members function is a coroutine that takes in a guild_id and user_ids list. It then iterates through the users list, popping off the first user id from the user_ids list and passing it to unban_member function of each client. If there is no response or if there was an error, it will return None. Otherwise, it will yield back the response.

Parameters:

  • self – Represent the instance of the class

  • guild_id – int: Specify the guild id of the server you want to unban members from

  • user_ids – list[int]: Store the list of user ids to unban

Returns:

async get(url: str, *, allow_redirects: bool = True, **kwargs: Any) → ClientResponse[source]

The get function is a wrapper for the get function in the ClientSession class. It allows us to use asyncio’s await syntax, which makes it easier to write asynchronous code. The get function takes a url and returns an object of type ClientResponse.

Parameters:

  • self – Represent the instance of the class

  • url – str: Specify the url to be requested

  • * – Unpack the tuple and the ** parameter is used to unpack the dictionary

  • allow_redirects – bool: Determine whether the client will follow redirects

  • **kwargs –

    Any: Pass in any additional parameters that are not specified

Returns:

A clientresponse object

The request function is a wrapper around the ClientSession.request function, which handles ratelimits and other exceptions that may occur during requests. It also adds an additional cooldown to the Retry-After header value.

  • method – str: Determine the type of request

async create_session() → None[source]

The create_session function is used to create a new session for the bot. This function is called when the bot starts up, and also when it needs to reconnect. The session object contains all of the information about how many requests have been made, and how long until more can be made.

self – Refer to the current instance of a class

run_async(function: Awaitable) → None[source]

The run_async function is a helper function that allows you to run an asyncio coroutine in the background. It takes a single argument, which must be an awaitable object (such as a coroutine). It runs the event loop until the awaitable completes and then returns. This is useful for running tasks in parallel with other code.

Parameters:

  • self – Access the attributes and methods of a class

  • function – Awaitable: Specify the type of the parameter function

Returns:

None
